      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Property Under Power of Attorney in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When an owner is elderly, incapacitated, or unable to manage their affairs, an attorney may need to sell on their behalf. Here is what attorneys and families need to understand before the campaign begins.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most property sales in Queensland follow a straightforward path: the owner signs the contract and transfer documents, and settlement proceeds. But a growing number of sales each year involve a different set of circumstances. The registered owner may be elderly and living in residential care, incapacitated following a medical event, living overseas with limited ability to attend to their affairs, or simply no longer able to manage financial decisions. In those situations, selling may need to proceed through a power of attorney, and the process carries legal requirements that every attorney and family member should understand before instructing an agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">General POA versus enduring POA: a critical distinction</h2>
      <p>Queensland law recognises two main types of power of attorney relevant to property transactions. A general power of attorney grants another person authority to act on the donor's behalf, but it automatically lapses if the donor loses mental capacity. This means a general POA is generally unsuitable for sales involving an owner who has or may develop cognitive impairment. An enduring power of attorney, by contrast, remains valid if the donor loses mental capacity, provided it was executed while the donor had capacity and the document specifically states that the attorney's authority continues through incapacity. For property sales where the owner is elderly or unwell, an enduring POA is almost always the instrument that will be used.</p>

      <p>The attorney named in the document can be any adult the donor chooses: a family member, a close friend, a solicitor, or a trustee company such as the Public Trustee of Queensland or a private trustee. The choice of attorney matters. Whoever is appointed has legal obligations to the donor that are enforceable and can give rise to personal liability if breached.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the attorney is legally required to do</h2>
      <p>Acting under a power of attorney is not a free hand to deal with someone's property as you see fit. Queensland's Powers of Attorney Act 1998 imposes specific duties on attorneys. The attorney must act in the donor's best interests at all times, not in their own interests or the interests of other family members. They must avoid conflicts of interest, keep the donor's finances completely separate from their own, and maintain proper records of every transaction. These are not aspirational guidelines. They are legal obligations, and breaching them can result in the attorney being held personally liable and required to compensate the donor or their estate.</p>

      <p>In the context of a property sale, the duty to act in the donor's best interests has direct practical implications. The attorney cannot sell the property to themselves, a family member, or an associated entity at below-market value. They must take reasonable steps to achieve a fair market price, which in practice means engaging a reputable agent, marketing the property properly, and not accepting an offer that is obviously below what the market would deliver. If the attorney wants to purchase the property themselves or sell to a related party, they will need a court order or the donor's prior written consent given while the donor had capacity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Registration before the POA can be used in a transaction</h2>
      <p>This is the step that catches families by surprise. Even if a valid enduring POA exists and has been properly executed, it cannot be used in a Queensland property transaction until it has been registered with the Queensland Titles Registry. Registration requires lodging the original document along with the prescribed form and fee. The process is not complicated, but it takes time, and it must be completed before the contract is signed. If the property is listed for sale and an offer comes in before the POA is registered, the attorney cannot execute the contract. Solicitors who deal regularly with these transactions will attend to registration as part of their engagement, but families managing this without professional assistance sometimes discover the requirement only when it becomes an obstacle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the attorney signs the transaction documents</h2>
      <p>When an attorney signs a contract or transfer on behalf of the donor, they sign in a specific way that identifies their capacity. The standard form is: [Donor's full name] by [Attorney's full name] their attorney pursuant to a Power of Attorney registered [registration details]. Your solicitor will advise you on the exact execution requirements for the contract, transfer, and any other documents involved in the transaction. Buyers' solicitors will scrutinise these documents carefully, particularly in sales involving registered POAs, so having everything in order from the outset avoids delays at settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the Public Trustee becomes involved</h2>
      <p>If a property owner lacks mental capacity and there is no valid enduring POA in place, the situation becomes considerably more complex. The property cannot be sold without authorisation from the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal (QCAT) or the Supreme Court. QCAT can appoint an administrator to manage the owner's financial affairs, including real property. The Public Trustee of Queensland is frequently appointed in these cases, though a family member can also apply to be appointed as administrator. The process takes longer than a straightforward POA sale, involves legal fees and court costs, and can be emotionally difficult for families who are already dealing with a loved one's incapacity. It is a process that could have been avoided with a properly executed enduring POA while the owner still had capacity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers and their solicitors will want to see</h2>
      <p>Buyers purchasing a property where the seller is acting under a POA are entitled to scrutinise the arrangement carefully. Their solicitors will review the registered POA document to confirm it is an enduring POA, that it was validly executed, that it covers real property transactions, and that it has been properly registered. If there is any question about the donor's capacity at the time the POA was executed, buyers may seek additional evidence. This is not obstruction. It is reasonable due diligence, and an attorney selling a property should expect it and be prepared for it.</p>

      <p>As the instructing agent, I work directly with the attorney's solicitor to ensure all documentation is in order before the property goes to market. Flagging the POA structure to prospective buyers at the right stage of negotiations, and having the solicitor available to address questions promptly, keeps the campaign moving without unnecessary delays. POA sales can proceed just as smoothly as any other sale with proper preparation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Engage a solicitor experienced in POA transactions</h2>
      <p>If you are an attorney about to instruct an agent to sell a property on the donor's behalf, the single most important thing you can do before any other step is to engage a Queensland solicitor with experience in POA property transactions. They will confirm whether the POA is valid and appropriate for a property sale, attend to registration if it has not already been done, advise you on your obligations as attorney, prepare the contract and transfer documents, and handle the settlement. Attempting to manage a POA sale without specialist legal advice is not advisable, even for attorneys who are themselves professionals in other fields.</p>

